Security audit found that `SquadDash\OpenAiTtsProvider.cs` in `SpeakAsync` creates a temp `.mp3` file and never deletes it:
```csharp
var tempPath = Path.ChangeExtension(Path.GetTempFileName(), ".mp3");
await File.WriteAllBytesAsync(tempPath, mp3Bytes, ct);
// file is opened by MediaPlayer but never deleted
```
Over many TTS calls this accumulates potentially-sensitive audio in `%TEMP%`.

Fix: Subscribe to the `MediaPlayer.MediaEnded` event and delete `tempPath` from there. Also handle the `MediaFailed` event to delete on failure. Use a try/catch around the delete since the file may already be gone. Example:
```csharp
var p = new MediaPlayer();
p.Open(new Uri(tempPath));
p.MediaEnded  += (_, _) => { try { File.Delete(tempPath); } catch { } };
p.MediaFailed += (_, _) => { try { File.Delete(tempPath); } catch { } };
p.Play();
```
No other files need to change.
